    <h1>LOOKS OF NEW CHRONOTOPI&#xAD;A</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-09"><time>2021-01-09</time></a>
        - <span>HOME DECOR</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>NOR­MAL</p>
    <p>What will our homes look like in the near fu­ture? Here are the top three trends shap­ing our in­te­ri­ors now and how you can adapt them into your own do­main.</p>
    <p>There is no in­stant an­ti­dote to the tri­als and tribu­la­tions left by the year 2020, nev­er­the­less the ar­rival of 2021 brings with it hope and prom­ise of re­cov­ery. Here are three dom­i­nant styles that and how to adapt them.</p>
    <p>BIO­PHILIA</p>
    <p>Plant par­ent­ing is one of the most pop­u­lar ways to bat­tle the pan­demic stress. It is ther­a­peu­tic, re­ward­ing and ir­re­sistibly In­sta­grammable.</p>
    <p>Bio­philia, or love for na­ture, has long been shap­ing our do­mes­tic en­vi­ron­ment, and again, the pan­demic has high­lighted the bene  t of bio­philic de­sign, es­pe­cially in Sin­ga­pore’s dense and ver­ti­cal ur­ban en­vi­ron­ment. In­cor­po­rat­ing bio­philia in the de­sign of your home is not that com­pli­cated.</p>
    <p>Here are a few ways:</p>
    <p>TURN YOUR BAL­CONY INTO A GAR­DEN</p>
    <p>All you need are some planters and a lot of pa­tience and love. No bal­cony space is too small, though it is im­por­tant to re­search the kind of plants suit­able for the level of care that you can com­mit to.</p>
    <p>USE MA­TE­RI­ALS THAT AGE GRACE­FULLY</p>
    <p>Par­tially in  uenced by the in­creas­ing pop­u­lar­ity of sus­tain­able fur­nish­ing, home­own­ers are now in­cor­po­rat­ing nat­u­ral ma­te­ri­als that gain patina with time into their decor. Think of aged wood and verdi­gris on cop­per and any ma­te­rial that   ts the wabi-sabi aes­thetic like Corten steel.</p>
    <p>GET RID OF THE CLUT­TER</p>
    <p>Take spe­cial care of ca­bles and elec­tron­ics, so you can re­con  gure your space in a ji  y with­out trip­ping over wires.</p>
    <p>“Chronotopi­a” is de­rived from the word “chrono­topic”, which means “of a speci  c time and place”. Hence, chronotopi­a at home refers to a space that can ful  l the func­tion de­manded of it in a speci  c time and place.</p>
    <p>In short: a   ex­i­ble, adapt­able space that can morph smoothly from one func­tion to an­other. This word has been used to de­scribe the adapt­abil­ity of public spa­ces, like when a car park be­comes a fes­ti­val venue.</p>

